Source: Newswire briefs [edited]
[A] Japan From: AFX News - Asia 24 Mar 2003 17:53
2 more people in Japan have been identified as possible [cases of SARS],
the health ministry said yesterday. The latest findings bring the tally of
suspected cases of SARS in Japan to 4, health officials said.
[B] Canada From: Canada.com / CP 25 Mar 2003
<http://www.canada.com/health/story.html?id=C6B2F0C9-7FBB-40BC-AD97-EE8233A597BD>
Public health officials in Toronto moved for the first time to quarantine
people who have been in contact with a case of SARS and who are showing
some symptoms of the disease. Officials said about 25 people who appear
symptomatic, and their close family contacts have been ordered to stay home
for a period of 10 days. That is believed to be the outside limit of the
infectious period of the disease. Health Minister Tony Clement announced
that Ontario had moved to make SARS a reportable disease Tuesday, giving
public health officials the power to order people to remain in quarantine
if necessary.
The number of probable cases of SARS in the province jumped to 18 from 10,
with 5 people remaining as suspect cases. Elsewhere in Canada, there is a
probable case in Vancouver and 2 suspected cases in Alberta. 3 people have
died.
The new cases are in health-care workers from Scarborough Grace Hospital,
where a patient who later died of SARS was treated in mid-March 2003. A man
who shared an emergency department room with him also contracted the
disease and died last Friday. The health-care workers -- who include
nurses, doctors, technicians, and paramedics -- treated the man before
worldwide attention was drawn to the fact that a mysterious, contagious,
and potentially fatal disease had spread from Southeast Asia. As such,
they were not taking the high level of care -- using special masks, gowns,
and treating patients in isolation -- that is now being used for SARS
cases. To date none of the staff in other Toronto hospitals caring for
SARS patients have shown signs of the disease. "We are taking steps to
contain the spread of SARS and to make sure people who have been exposed
are safely isolated where they are cared for," said Dr. Colin d'Cunha,
chief medical officer for Ontario.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In today's update there is an increase of 31 new cases reported to the WHO
since yesterday's report, of which the majority have occurred in Hong
Kong. Of note is that in yesterday's update, Spain was listed as having a
probable case, whereas Spain is not on today's update as having a probable
case. This is being mentioned to further highlight the state of flux of
these reports, due to the absence of a definitive diagnostic test to
confirm that these cases of respiratory illness are in fact due to
SARS. We are trying to present the most up-to-date and accurate case
counts and information on disease transmission, geographic areas with cases
identified, and geographic areas where secondary transmission has occurred.
The newswire report on the suspected cases among health care professionals
in Ontario, Canada has not been confirmed as yet on the Health Canada
website; hence this information is likely to change. Of note is that the
Ontario Provincial Department of Health has implemented a quarantine on the
suspected cases and their close contacts. The newswire report on 4
suspected cases in Japan is not reflected in the WHO reports, and suggests
that they do not meet the criteria to be classified as probable
cases. (see WHO case definitions
at:<http://www.who.int/csr/sars/casedefinition/en/>- Mod.MPP]
